<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/1518e5f3b1f7817e9182c01f60f5d44e> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "WONING VAN DE KARI'NA OP DE TENTOONSTELLING 'SURINAME ZOALS HET LEEFT EN WERKT' (SEPT. 1953/JAN. 1954)" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/1518e5f3b1f7817e9182c01f60f5d44e> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Op de foto is een hut te zien van de Kalin'a indianen. Hij vormde een onderdeel van de tentoonstelling 'Suriname zoals het leeft en werkt'. Alle tentoongestelde objecten waren voorzien van teksten die zowel in het Nederlands als in het  Surinaams geschreven waren. \r\n\r\nDe tentoongestelde indianenhut stelt een woonkampje voor van de Kalin'a's. Het bestaat uit stijlen van hard hout, waarop een dakbedekking rust, gemaakt van een wilde bananensoort (paloeloe). De nok is afgedekt met palmblad. Bij de bouw van dergelijke hutten werd geen gebruik gemaakt van spijkers. De grotere balken rusten op ingekeepte posten, de hulplatten worden met bostouw (hier warimbo) vastgebonden. Meestal zijn alleen de zijwanden gesloten, soms ook (zoals hier) de achterwand. Hutten zoals deze, worden niet in het bos maar voornamelijk op opengekapte stukken woud of in de savannen gebouwd. \r\n\r\nBinnen het hutje waren gebruiksvoorwerpen te zien, die de huisraad - de dagelijkse gebruiksvoorwerpen van mannen en vrouwen - moest voorstellen.  [Joseph 1953: 11; Landsregering van Suriname 1953: 8.]\r\n\r\nVoor meer informatie, zie het werkstuk: 'The role of material culture in the political awakening of Suriname: an analysis of Tropenmuseum collection number 2345', Alderson 2007.\r\n\r\n\r\n----------------\r\nThis photograph shows the re-constructed Kalin'a hut, displayed here in the light hall of the Tropenmuseum as part of the 'Suriname zoals het leeft en werkt' exhibition.  As was strongly emphasized in the exhibition guide, this 'typical hut' was built 'entirely without nails'.  All of the displayed objects were clearly labeled. It appears that both the Dutch and Surinamese names were used. \r\nPhoto: KIT Tropenmuseum. \r\n\r\nInformation about the Indians (as presented in the exhibition guide):\r\nWithin the exhibition guide, the cultural attributes and traditions of the various Indian groups were extensively described. The different Indians tribes were split into five distinct tribes: the Arawak, Carib (Kalin'a's), Oayana's, Trio's and Wayarikoelé's.  According to the guide, each group has a different level of contact with the Dutch colonial authorities and other foreigners. The Wayarikoelé's, for example, were still living in the 'stone age', while the Oayana's lifestyle was heavily influenced by Western civilization. As is explained in the exhibition guide, the majority of Indians used to use handmade stone or clay baking pans when cooking; now they use metal. This is one of the only references to a Western influence in this guide. \r\n\r\nA life-sized Kalin'a hut, built in the traditional way, was used to display many of the objects associated with the Indians (seen in this photograph). The native materials used to build the hut were carefully described in the guide; both the traditional and Dutch names were used. Visible in the photographs of this display are small 'name tags' attached to most of the objects, presumably also written in both languages. As was strongly emphasized in the guide, this 'typical hut' was built 'entirely without nails'. [Joseph 1953: 11] Inside, the hut was equipped with the daily household items used by both men and women. According to this guide, the Indian men were responsible for making the hunting gear, weaving the baskets, acquiring the smoking gear (tobacco and pipes) and traditional (herbal) medicines. The women were responsible for growing and preparing the food and taking care of the children. The women also made the earthenware pots, spun the cotton and made the mats. Two sorts of mats were displayed in this exhibition, one made of cotton (Karibs model) and one made of the fibers of the Mauritian palm tree (Arowaks model). Also exhibited was a simple sugar press, made out of a block of wood and a pottery bowl (prapie). The importance of cassava for the Indians was also emphasized.  [Excerpt from the paper: The role of material culture in the political awakening of Suriname: an analysis of Tropenmuseum collection number 2345', Alderson 2007.]\r\n\r\n[J.Alderson 2007]" .
